Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 100 BC, the ancient Celtic festival of Samhain, celebrated on to mark the end of the harvest and the onset of winter, began. 

The Celts, who lived in what is now Ireland, the UK, and northern France, believed this night blurred the line between the living and the dead. They lit bonfires, wore costumes, and performed rituals to ward off spirits and seek guidance from Druids, the Celtic priests.

In the 8th century, Pope Gregory III established November 1 as All Saints Day, which integrated elements of Samhain, leading to the evening before being known as All Hallows Eve, or Halloween. By the 9th century, as Christianity spread, it further absorbed Celtic traditions, and November 2 became All Souls’ Day, honoring the dead in ways similar to Samhain.

While Halloween celebrations were limited in Puritan New England due to strict religious beliefs, they thrived in southern colonies where communal harvest celebrations emerged. With the arrival of Irish immigrants in the late 19th century, Halloween gained national popularity. These immigrants brought customs like dressing in costumes, where children went door-to-door asking for food, evolving into the modern trick-or-treating tradition.

By the late 1800s, there was a concerted effort in America to reshape Halloween into a community-focused holiday, emphasizing neighborly gatherings over its darker roots. This led to the rise of Halloween parties, featuring games, seasonal foods, and festive costumes. Newspapers and community leaders advocated for removing frightening elements, resulting in a Halloween that lost much of its superstitious and religious connotations by the early 20th century, focusing instead on fun and community spirit.

Name: Calvert, Ken
text:
Earlier this month, @HouseVetAffairs Chairman @RepBost and I held a Veteran Service Organization Roundtable in the 41st District. Here is our joint statement about the many concerns that were raised by veterans and VSO representatives:  

“On October 16, we met with local veterans and Veteran Service Organizations at the Palm Springs Air Museum to address critical issues in veterans' health care. Listening to veterans share their struggles with referral delays and inefficiencies at the Loma Linda VA, and the lack of accountability among senior VA leaders underscored the urgent need for veteran-centered reforms to hold failing leaders accountable. That’s why we’re leading H.R. 2478, the Restore VA Accountability Act, to bring accountability back to VA nationwide, for good.

One key concern raised was the lack of reliable transportation in the region, which forces many veterans to face unnecessary logistical barriers when it comes to receiving essential healthcare. This is unacceptable. We are committed to advancing legislation that holds the entire VA accountable – including Loma Linda VA employees – to ensure that no veteran encounters barriers when receiving the timely, high-quality care they have earned.

Together, we are fighting to create a health care system that prioritizes transparency, accountability, and respect for those who have served our country. Veterans gave their all for this nation, and it is our duty to honor that sacrifice by building a system that meets their needs no matter what.”

Name: Bentz, Cliff
text:
“This bill is the result of hundreds of hours of negotiation and collaboration by those who live, work, and recreate in Malheur County, The Burns Paiute Tribe, and many environmental organizations.  It is based on a bill introduced last year by Senator Ron Wyden.  It is a provisional bill, but it contains those elements needed to protect the land, plants, animals and communities that rely upon that land.  I want to thank the Senator for his personal involvement and for his staff’s work, and I look forward to successfully passing this bill out of the House within the next few weeks,” said Congressman Cliff Bentz.

“Congressman Bentz and I have been working together to pass Owyhee legislation before the end of the year. His announcement today of the upcoming hearing in the House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Public Lands on his "Oregon Owyhee Wilderness and Community Protection Act" takes a significant step forward toward achieving that goal,” Senator Ron Wyden said. “I applaud Congressman Bentz’s thoughtful and constructive approach and am looking forward, as we continue to work together on this bill, to success on legislation that leaves the farmers, ranchers, preservationists, Tribes and all the residents of Eastern Oregon the true winners of the economic and preservation gains this legislative approach can achieve.”

Name: Bentz, Cliff
text:
Exciting news! I am set to introduce my bill tomorrow that will protect the Owyhee Canyonlands and support those who live in and around this landscape.

Big Hungry outpost is a group of 78 residents who were stranded after a state bridge, which provided the only access in and out of the area, washed away.
 
Despite major challenges, they gathered together to clean up trees and mudslides and even came up with a ziplining delivery system, which involved cutting out landing spots for helicopters to drop off deliveries.
 
What another incredible example of resilience by a group of citizens who were initially alone fending for themselves from the devastation of Helene.

Name: Johnson, Mike
text:
The trust placed in many of America’s once-great universities has been broken. Today’s thorough report from Chairwoman Foxx and the Education and Workforce Committee shows students why they may want to consider getting a degree elsewhere.
 
Pro-Hamas encampments grew and were allowed to fester on college campuses in the aftermath of the horrific terrorist attack on October 7, 2023. Harvard chose not to stop students from shouting antisemitic phrases; Northwestern’s provost approved of boycotts of Israeli products and put radical anti-Israel faculty in charge of negotiations with pro-Hamas encampments; at Columbia, faculty obstructed plans to discipline antisemitic students who stormed a campus building; and at UCLA, officials stood by idly as illegal, antisemitic encampments endangered and violated the rights of Jewish students. In each instance, these institutions violated the law and their own codes of conduct. Across the board, too many of our ‘elite’ university classrooms have been transformed into training camps for anti-American and anti-Israel activism, subsidized by the taxpayer.
 
I’m thankful for Chairwoman Foxx’s work to expose university leaders’ willingness to coddle antisemites and their abject failure to protect Jewish students. Today’s report will be an important tool for Congress to use as we reassess federal funding for higher education.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1955, a bomb aboard United Airlines Flight 629 kills 44 people. 

The flight took off from Denver, bound for Portland. Just 11 minutes into the flight, the plane crashed near Longmont, killing all 39 passengers and five crew members. Initial investigations revealed signs of an explosion; wreckage analysis showed damage to the fuselage, and eyewitnesses reported seeing fireballs in the sky and on the ground.

As the investigation progressed, it became clear that the crash was not due to mechanical failure or pilot error. The FBI was called in to pursue a criminal investigation. A crucial lead emerged when investigators found that passenger Daisie E. King had been carrying newspaper clippings concerning her son, Jack Gilbert Graham, who had a criminal history involving forgery and was on a local most-wanted list. Notably, Graham was the beneficiary of at least $37,500 in life insurance policies on his mother, and there were reports of strained relations between them.

As the investigation deepened, FBI agents discovered detonating wire at Graham's residence. This prompted further interrogation, during which Graham confessed to his heinous act: he had constructed a homemade bomb using 25 sticks of dynamite, hidden it in his mother’s luggage, and set it to explode after a timed delay, having purchased a 60-minute timing device shortly before the flight.

Graham's motives were rooted in financial gain; in addition to the life insurance policies, he stood to inherit a significant sum upon his mother's death. Testimonies revealed frequent arguments between them, supporting the notion of a strained relationship leading to Graham's desperate act.

Ultimately, he was found guilty and sentenced to death, with his execution taking place in January 1957.

One lingering question about the case was why Graham was only charged with the murder of his mother despite the loss of 44 lives. Legal experts noted that this strategy was likely the most straightforward route to secure a death penalty conviction, as specific laws governing airline bombings had yet to be established.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, I’m honored to share the stories of our Hometown Heroes—those whose courage, selflessness, and dedication embody the very best of our community. Throughout my time in Congress, few experiences have been as humbling as recognizing those from our hometown who inspire real, lasting change, not only in PA-1 but throughout our nation. And just last week, we gathered together to celebrate some of these incredible heroes at our inaugural Hometown Heroes Celebration—an evening that reminded us all how remarkable our community truly is, thanks to these individuals who give so much of themselves without asking for recognition.
 
Our PA-1 Hometown Heroes lift others, foster unity, & inspire hope through quiet acts of bravery and compassion. They don’t seek the spotlight; they simply act, driven by duty & love for our community. In their stories, we find a powerful reminder that the goodness of everyday heroism shapes both our community & our country.

Name: Frankel, Lois
text:
Social Security and Medicare are essential benefits that our seniors have worked and paid for with each and every paycheck throughout their lives.

With over 350,000 seniors in Palm Beach County, I will always fight to protect, expand, and strengthen these vital programs. https://t.co/7jpKYDCpYc

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
One of our honored heroes, Joseph Fluehr III—a Funeral Director & Veterans Advocate—captured the sentiment we all felt, remarking: “As I looked around, I was truly struck by how many heroes are among us.” And indeed, our heroes are everywhere. They are people like Valerie Hamilton, who dedicates her life to creating enriching opportunities for our Children in Bristol; Jeff Bekos, the devoted Doylestown Dad (One Dads Mission) who cycled across the country to raise funds for the @RMHC in gratitude for the support he received during his daughter’s health battle; the committed members of Levittown's Queen Bees Foundation, who unite to uplift those in need; Chrissy Elberson, a @BensalemSchools teacher who goes beyond the classroom to empower our future leaders; the members of Shir Ami Reform Synagogue in Newtown, who collected nearly 40,000 pounds of food to feed our neighbors in need; Plumstead Township Police Chief David Mettin, a steadfast public servant for over 37 years; young Layla Peck, a 7-year-old who organized a surprise celebration for one of our cherished World War II veterans; the Bucks Dragon Boat Senior Ladies A Team, who together saved a life; and Elizabeth Todderud, who handcrafted over 300 blankets for local military families welcoming new life. Each of them, along with so many others, reminds us of what we can achieve through everyday acts of kindness and strength.
 
I look forward to continuing to honor remarkable individuals and organizations who show us that, even in challenging times, there are still people working every day to make the world a better place. So, this week, please join me in thanking our Hometown Heroes from the past year—we’re a stronger community because of them, and may we all continue to be inspired by their service and goodwill.

Friday in the First

Having spent over 23 years as the band director at Elizabeth City Middle School, Mr. Simmons takes great joy in witnessing the happiness on a student’s face once they learn to perform a piece of music. Additionally, he is the point of contact for the Elizabeth City Ukulele Group.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
I’m excited to announce the opening of the new Customs Trade Partnership Against Terrorism (CTPAT) Field Office at the World Trade Bridge in Laredo. I secured funding for this office as part of my commitment to support Customs and Border Protection (CBP) operations.
 
The CTPAT program is essential for enhancing international supply chain security while facilitating the movement of legitimate, low-risk cargo. This office will handle program applications, assess eligibility, certify new members, and maintain ongoing accounts, covering Laredo and cross-border cities in Tamaulipas, Mexico.
 
This office is a crucial step in strengthening trade security and promoting economic growth in our community. I want to extend my thanks to JD Gonzalez, President of NCBFAA, and the Laredo trade community for their leadership and support in making this project a reality. 

I’m dedicated to ensuring we have the resources necessary to enhance border security and support local economies.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
What a wonderful afternoon with my friends at 
The Bridges at Warwick! I was thrilled to engage in meaningful conversations with residents, their families, and the dedicated staff members. Our discussions revolved around the SENIOR Act, a crucial piece of legislation that I am championing to address the pressing challenges faced by assisted living providers in our community and across the nation. This legislation is designed to enhance access and affordability in senior care while addressing the workforce challenges that directly impact the quality of care our seniors deserve.
 
Since my first day in Congress, I have made it my priority to be a steadfast advocate for our seniors—the true heart and soul of our community—and for the individuals who work tirelessly to support them. Thank you to Kim Sager, Executive Director, and the exceptional Bridges team for your incredible work and service; I look forward to continuing working alongside you in our shared mission to ensure our seniors are thriving, supported, and cared for.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1847, The Hughes Flying Boat, also known as the "Spruce Goose," flies for the first and last time. 

Howard Hughes, a successful Hollywood producer, founded the Hughes Aircraft Company in 1932 and made several aviation records, including a transcontinental flight in 1937 and a round-the-world trip in 1938. After the U.S. entered World War II, Hughes was commissioned to develop the H-4 flying boat. Originally conceived by Henry Kaiser, the project fell to Hughes due to Kaiser’s withdrawal. With steel in short supply, the aircraft was primarily made of wood, which led to its nickname. It was intended to transport over 700 troops.

The development cost $23 million and took so long that the war ended before its completion in 1946. Critics questioned its viability, prompting Congress to require a demonstration of airworthiness. Hughes surprised thousands of spectators by flying the Spruce Goose for a mile over Long Beach Harbor.

Despite this successful flight, the Spruce Goose never entered production due to concerns about its wooden structure. After becoming increasingly reclusive, Hughes maintained the aircraft in a climate-controlled hangar until his death in 1976. The Spruce Goose is now displayed at the Evergreen Aviation Museum in McMinnville, Oregon.

E60: @GovParsonMO | Reflecting on Service, Missouri, and America

(01:49) Motivation to Serve

(04:38) The Military Recruiting Crisis
(05:53) Afghanistan Withdrawal
(08:52) Running for Polk County Sheriff

(17:17) Toughest Decisions as Governor
++ much more!

In this episode of Mark Alford's America, Congressman Mark Alford sits down with Missouri’s 57th Governor, Mike Parson, at his Kansas City office. Governor Parson reflects on a lifetime of service, from his days in the U.S. Army to serving as Polk County Sheriff, and his path to the Governor’s office.

He shares insights on the values driving his leadership, his commitment to Missouri’s infrastructure and workforce development, and his dedication to creating opportunities for future generations. Governor Parson also shares the inside story of how he found out he would become governor and what those first few days were like.

Tune in for an inspiring conversation with @GovParsonMO.

Also available in full on Spotify and Apple Podcast:

Ensuring veterans can access high-quality healthcare to live healthy lives should be one of Congress’s highest priorities.

I’ve been working across the aisle to make it a reality for Southwest Washington veterans – because they put their lives on the line to protect freedom and democracy.

Where you choose to live shouldn’t impact the care you can access, so I introduced a bipartisan bill to expand transportation services for rural veterans to more easily get to their medical appointments – and I testified in support of it before the House Veterans Affairs Committee.

I also directly urged the VA Secretary to listen to the calls of Lewis County veterans to reopen a clinic – and I co-led the VET MEDS Act, which is now law to support veterans’ access to VA-certified specialists and examiners in rural and high-need communities.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Our community recently came together to honor the life and legacy of an extraordinary Bucks County hero—@USMC Lance Corporal John F. Muffler. A Neshaminy School District graduate, Corp. Muffler enlisted in the Marines directly after high school. But tragically, on October 23, 1983, he was among the 241 American servicemen who lost their lives in the devastating suicide bombing of the U.S. Marine barracks in Beirut—the deadliest single-day loss for U.S. Marines since Iwo Jima in 1945—he was just 19-years-old. 

In honor of his service and sacrifice, the Pine Street (Route 413) bridge over Route 1 in Middletown Township has been officially named the Lance Corporal John F. Muffler Memorial Bridge. Please join me in honoring Corp. Muffler’s bravery and patriotism and in extending our deepest sympathies to his family and loved ones. His loss continues to be profoundly felt across our community.

Thank you to State Senator Frank Farry, PA State Rep. Joe Hogan, and the incredible Ed Preston for your efforts to ensure Corp. Muffler’s legacy lives on forever.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
ICYMI: Following the unveiling of the Rosie The Riveter Congressional Gold Medal earlier this year, I recently held a Congressional Gold Medal Ceremony to present our remarkable Rosies of PA-1 with their own Congressional Gold Medals—it was an unforgettable and truly inspiring celebration. 

For far too long, the contributions of these trailblazers went unrecognized, which is why I introduced the Rosie the Riveter Congressional Gold Medal Act—signed into law in 2020—to ensure these extraordinary women received the long overdue honor they so deserved.

The “We Can Do It” spirit was alive and vibrantly displayed by four of our amazing Rosies, 102-year-old Rita Colella, 102-year-old Dorothy Trate, 97-year-old Michaeline “Mickey” Kryven, and my dear friend, 98-year-old Mae Krier, as well as the wonderful families of our PA-1 Rosies who have passed, as we recognized the amazing women of our community who helped our nation win World War II. 

Watch the recap below: ⬇️

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1979, the Iran Hostage Crisis begins when students loyal to Ayatollah Khomeini, an Iranian religious leader, stormed the U.S. embassy in Tehran, taking 90 hostages in a dramatic act of protest. 

Their anger stemmed from the U.S. allowing the deposed Shah, who had been overthrown in Iran's 1979 revolution, to enter the country for medical treatment. The students, part of a radical Islamic movement, threatened to kill hostages if any rescue attempts were made, escalating tensions between Iran and the United States.

In the wake of the takeover, Khomeini solidified his power, and after a brief period, the students began releasing non-American hostages, along with women and minorities, whom Khomeini described as oppressed by American society. However, 52 American diplomats and embassy staff remained captives for 14 months as President Jimmy Carter struggled to resolve the crisis through diplomacy. 

Carter's inability to secure a resolution was compounded by a failed military rescue mission in April 1980, which resulted in the deaths of eight U.S. servicemen. This debacle further eroded public confidence in his leadership and severely impacted his reelection campaign. 

After months of tense negotiations, a deal was finally reached, and the hostages were released on January 20, 1981, just minutes after Reagan took office, illustrating the enduring animosity towards Carter.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
November is Military Families Month, which allows us to reflect on the immense sacrifice of the mothers, fathers, brothers, sisters, and other significant others who support our men and women in uniform at home and abroad. To improve the quality of life for our gold star, blue star, and all our military families, we are cosponsoring the following three bipartisan bills:

▪️H.R. 3651, the Love Lives on Act of 2023, a bill to prevent the VA from terminating benefits for surviving spouses of fallen servicemembers solely because they remarry.
 
▪️H.R. 4944, the Military Families and Surviving Spouses Benefits Enhancement Act, a bill that supports military families by easing the financial burden on active-duty military spouses when they are challenged with the loss of employment due to the Servicemember's change of duty location.

▪️H.R.7966, the Protecting our Service Members and their Families from Predatory Financial Practices Act, legislation to require the verification of the financial independence of financial services counselors providing services to members of the Armed Forces.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
I hosted a roundtable discussion in Chico with the Federal Home Loan Bank of San Francisco and local banks, developers, and housing advocates to address the need to build additional housing and particularly the affordable housing crisis. Economic challenges, high insurance costs, and wildfires have made it important for us to come together and find real-world solutions. We explored how public-private partnerships and regulatory reforms can help increase housing supply and affordability, and I appreciate everyone who participated for their insights and dedication.

The Chico Housing Action Team has received $100,000 in grant funding through the FHL Bank’s AHEAD program to enhance its efforts in supporting those seeking affordable housing. FHLSF has also given over $750,000 to middle-income residents of our district for down payment assistance. Together, we can create opportunities that protect our way of life and stimulate our local economy.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Community growth demands action, which is why I fought to secure over $53M in Community Project Funding for transformative projects across PA-1. Each of these projects, while unique in focus, is united by a common mission: to uplift, empower, and build a stronger future for everyone in our district.

ICYMI, some project highlights include:

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Empowering Our Seniors: $4 Million for the new Bristol Township Senior Center to provide a safe, supportive environment for seniors, fostering community and access to essential resources.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Expanding Access to Quality Healthcare: Over $2 Million for @DoylestownHlth and Grand View Health to bring life-saving treatments closer to home and reduce patient wait times.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Combatting PFAS & Water Contamination: Over $4 Million for Horsham Water and Sewer Authority and Langhorne Borough as part of my ongoing efforts to safeguard our waters.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Supporting Mental Health & Behavioral Health: $2 Million for @WoodsServices and @mystlukes, and the launch of Bright Path Center, PA’s first crisis stabilization center for mental health and recovery.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Revitalizing Communities: $8.85 Million for Borough of Morrisville PA, $2.2 Million for Historic Bristol Borough, and $1.2 Million for Tullytown Borough to fuel economic growth, enhance quality of life, support our youth, and strengthen infrastructure.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Supporting Small Business Growth: $500,000 for Startup Bucks Fund to help small businesses thrive amidst economic challenges.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Enhancing Public Safety & Supporting Our First Responders: $1.4 Million to upgrade Bucks County 911 and @BucksCountyGovt Emergency Services, equipping responders to keep us safe.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Breaking the Cycle of Poverty: $1 Million for Bucks County Opportunity Council to empower families with pathways to economic self-sufficiency.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: ✅ Fighting Homelessness & Hunger: $2.9 Million for @FSABucksCo to build a new emergency shelter, and $2.9 Million for @UWBucks to combat food insecurity.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
I look forward to working alongside our community leaders as these projects progress, and championing initiatives like these, focused on real, measurable impact, to ensure PA-1 continues to thrive.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1940, Franklin D. Roosevelt was elected to an unprecedented third term as President of the United States, becoming the first U.S. president in history to win more than two terms in office. 

Roosevelt, who had already served as president for nearly eight years, defeated his Republican opponent by a wide margin, securing 84.5% of the electoral vote. His victory reflected the continued public support for his leadership during one of the most challenging periods in American history.

FDR's presidency was marked by bold and transformative actions aimed at addressing the Great Depression and guiding the nation through the early years of World War II. Under his New Deal programs, Roosevelt introduced groundbreaking economic reforms, including Social Security, labor rights protections, and public works projects, which sought to provide relief, recovery, and reform to a country devastated by economic collapse.

As he campaigned for his third term in 1940, Roosevelt was also faced with the growing threat of global conflict. World War II was already raging in Europe, and Roosevelt had begun to prepare the U.S. for its eventual involvement, despite widespread isolationist sentiment at home.

Roosevelt's third term would prove to be pivotal, as the United States officially entered World War II in December 1941, following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor. Roosevelt's leadership during the war would shape not only the future of the United States but also the world order in the post-war era.

FDR's election for a third term marked a significant moment in U.S. history, signaling the nation's confidence in his ability to navigate turbulent times. His continued presidency, however, also sparked debates about presidential term limits, leading to the eventual passage of the 22nd Amendment in 1951, which formally restricted U.S. presidents to two terms in office.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
Congratulations to the Machinist Union workers for their courage and tenacity. At great personal risk they stood up for each other for two challenging months. They set an example for working people everywhere – to fight for fair wages and benefits – and they were hugely successful. The deal that Machinists and Boeing came together last night to agree on delivers better benefits for Boeing workers, including a wage increase, stronger retirement plans, and other significant benefit improvements.
 
"I will always support the rights of workers to organize and collectively bargain for better working conditions. I’m grateful today for the many leaders who rose to the occasion during these negotiations. Much is owed to Machinists President Job Holden, Boeing CEO Kelly Ortberg, and the Biden-Harris Administration’s Acting Labor Secretary Julie Su for their expertise and leadership in this process.

"This new agreement should represent a new chapter for Boeing. For many decades, Boeing was a pillar of American innovation and manufacturing, but in recent times its felt like they have chosen to prioritize shareholders and investors over their own employees. I am hopeful that with this successful negotiation with the Machinists, that Boeing can learn from this experience and get back to where the company came from: a business focused not only on short-term profits but on building the best airplanes in the world. It’s their middle- and working-class employees that build value not only in Boeing but also in our broader economy. I’m glad to see their work being recognized with this agreement that sets a new standard for workers in the aerospace industry.
 
"Livable wages, strong retirement options, and good benefits should be the standard for workers everywhere. I am hopeful that this new chapter will bring great success to Boeing and all of its employees.”
